[4]According to tradition, the robe (or better, part of it) was in the possession of st. Helena, mother of emperor Constantine the Great, who would have delivered at st. Agrizio, archbishop of Trier, in order for them to Trier.
[5]Wetzer und Welte, Kirchenlexikon, Band 9, Seite 333, Herder, 1852, Zur Trierer Tradition des Hl.
[6]Rockes however, Because more and more often we saw that he was forced to apportavi repairs, and to take measures for its protection, the situation of the original tunic was altered several times.
[7]According to various inspection, it was just more layers of different materials, that in the course of time, were assembled on a unique core.Untersuchungsbericht von 1891La the diocese of Trier describes the current situation of the relic on its Web site, so, in 2011, reported: "The shreds of cloth in the front part of the tunica, consisting of today, seen from the inside to the outside, a satin, silky, tulle brown and a grey taffeta.
[8]This taffeta and is in addition to a layer of old fragments of fabric, which are connected by an elastic support.
[9]The part of the tunic consists of satin, silky rossobruno, tulle brownish, fine gauze, silk, felt, taffeta green, an additional layer of felt and gauze of silk.
[10]From here we can deduce, that the wool fibres, which form the felt, in part by connecting it, in part, wrenching, represent the core of the fabric, the age of which cannot be well determined."
Diagonal:3, Size:5
[12]Rock Originally the Sacred Tunic was mentioned for the first time on may 1, 1196, when archbishop of Trier, John, consecrated the main altar of the then newly erected in the choir of the Trier Cathedral and took in the relics.
[13]When the emperor Maximilian I came to Trier on the occasion of the meeting of the parliament of the kingdom of 1512, he asked to see the Holy Tunic.
[14]Archbishop Richard von Greiffenklau zu Vollrads he, like many other bishops and prelates in the presence of the emperor, open the altar.
[15]After the divine Office, celebrated in memory of the deceased wife of Maximilian I, the citizens asked in a loud voice to the exposure of the tunic.
[16]The Chapter of the Cathedral he had built, so say the woodcuts of the era, a balcony on the west side of the apse, from which, as from 30 June took place numerous performances.Up to 1517 there were, annually, pilgrimages to the Holy Tunic in Trier.
Diagonal:4, Size:5
[17]At the suggestion of pope Leo X, the pilgrimages were to be held subsequently in accordance with the trips to the shrine of Aachen.
[18]So the subsequent performances were established every seven years: 1524; 1531; 1538 and 1545.
[19]Because of the disorders consequent on the reformation and the wars, the cadence of the exposures was abandoned, and finally ceased.
[20]The Sacred Tunic was kept, from 1632 to 1794, except for a few break in the Fortress of Ehrenbreitstein in Koblenz.
[21]Thither bishop Johann Philipp von Walderdorff, the made expose on the 4th of may 1765, preparing for the occasion for a pilgrimage.
Diagonal:5, Size:8
[24]Wallfahrt von 1765, The last elector of Trier]], Clement Wenceslaus of Saxony, took her to Augusta, but in 1810 returned to Trier.The first literary quote of the Holy Tunic is in a work in verse Orendel, dating back to the 1190 about.
[25]Up to now the pilgrimages on the occasion of the exhibition of the Holy Tunic, took place in the years 1513, 1514, 1515, 1516, 1517, 1524, 1531, 1538, 1545, 1655, 1765 (Koblenz), 1810, 1844, 1891, 1933, 1959 and 1996.
[26]In 1810, on the occasion of the return from Augusta, the tunic was exposed for 18 days and there was an influx of 220,000 pilgrims altogether.For the exposition of 1844, which lasted 7 weeks, went to Trier a million pilgrims.
[27]This exhibition gave rise to frequent public debates.
[28]It was the occasion that brought the writer Otto von Corvin to write the book anti-clerical Pfaffenspiegel (The mirror of the priest) and the humorist and writer and politician Rudolf Löwenstein to write poetry satirical Freifrau von Droste-vischering fortress zum heil'gen Rock nach Trier ging (The baroness of Droste-vischering fortress went to the Holy Tunic in Trier) on the satirical magazine Kladderadatsch (a loud crash).
[29]The priest Johannes Ronge wrote a letter of protest to the bishop of Trier, Wilhelm Arnoldi, in which he stigmatizzava publicly idolatry, which, according to him, led to the pilgrimages to the relics.
[31]In 1891 appeared in the roman press, in Paris, london and cairo, the announcement of bishop Michael Felix Korum, a new exhibition of the Holy Tunic and the consequent organization of pilgrimages, which took place in the environment of international and not only German.
[33]Meyers Konversationslexikon 1905 In 1933, on the occasion of the Holy Year took place the exhibition of the Sara Tunic close to the Reichskonkordat.
Diagonal:6, Size:2
[32]The number of pilgrims who came to Trier for the occasion was approximately two million.
[34]From 23 June until 8 September of that year they came to visit the relic more than two million pilgrims.The last pilgrimage took place for the public exposition of the Tunic it came to pass in 1996 under the motto Mit Jesus Christus auf dem Weg (On the way with Jesus Christ) and about 700,000 pilgrims came to Trier for the occasion.Since then, the diocese of Trier organized the annual "Decade of the Sacred Tunic", ten days on the type of regional Katholikentag (Day of the catholics).
